INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Data Processing and Aggregations$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which processor lets you parse a string field as a date and store the result in a target field/timezone?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"date"},{"id":"b","text":"convert"},{"id":"c","text":"gsub"},{"id":"d","text":"json"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$The `date` processor parses one or more date formats and writes a timestamp (often `@timestamp`). `convert` changes scalar types, `gsub` does regex replace, `json` parses a JSON string.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/processors.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Ingest processor reference"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p1$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which processor lets you parse a string field as a date and store the result in a target field/timezone?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Data Processing and Aggregations$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$How do you attach a default ingest pipeline so every write to an index is processed automatically?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Set index.default_pipeline in the index settings"},{"id":"b","text":"Add a processor to elasticsearch.yml"},{"id":"c","text":"Use a search template"},{"id":"d","text":"Set cluster.routing.allocation.pipeline"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$The index setting `index.default_pipeline` (or `index.final_pipeline`) runs a pipeline on every indexed document without specifying `?pipeline=` per request. Pipelines are not configured in `elasticsearch.yml`.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/ingest.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Ingest pipelines"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p1$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$How do you attach a default ingest pipeline so every write to an index is processed automatically?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Installation and Configuration$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$On a fresh Elasticsearch 8.x install, what is true about the security configuration by default?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Security is disabled and must be enabled manually."},{"id":"b","text":"Security (TLS + authentication) is enabled automatically on first start, with an enrollment token generated for additional nodes/Kibana."},{"id":"c","text":"Only API key auth is available; TLS is never configured."},{"id":"d","text":"Security requires a paid license."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["b"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Since 8.0 the Elastic Stack security features are on by default: TLS for the transport and HTTP layers is auto-configured and an enrollment token is printed for joining nodes and Kibana. Basic security is free.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/configuring-stack-security.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Configure security"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$On a fresh Elasticsearch 8.x install, what is true about the security configuration by default?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Installation and Configuration$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which `node.roles` value makes a node a coordinating-only node (no master, data, or ingest duties)?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"node.roles: [ coordinating ]"},{"id":"b","text":"node.roles: []"},{"id":"c","text":"node.roles: [ none ]"},{"id":"d","text":"node.coordinating: true"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["b"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$A coordinating-only node is configured with an EMPTY roles list: `node.roles: []`. There is no explicit `coordinating` role keyword — every node implicitly coordinates; removing all other roles yields a coordinating-only node.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/modules-node.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Node roles"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which `node.roles` value makes a node a coordinating-only node (no master, data, or ingest duties)?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Installation and Configuration$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which setting in `elasticsearch.yml` controls the network address the node binds to and publishes for client and inter-node traffic?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"network.host"},{"id":"b","text":"http.cors.host"},{"id":"c","text":"path.data"},{"id":"d","text":"cluster.routing.host"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`network.host` sets the bind/publish address (e.g. `0.0.0.0` or a specific IP). `path.data` is the data directory; `http.cors.host` is CORS-only; `cluster.routing.host` is not a setting.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/settings.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Configuring Elasticsearch"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which setting in `elasticsearch.yml` controls the network address the node binds to and publishes for client and inter-node traffic?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Installation and Configuration$tv2$, 3, $tv2$MULTI$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Select ALL true statements about JVM heap and system configuration for an Elasticsearch node.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Heap is typically set no more than ~50% of physical RAM and below the ~32 GB compressed-oops threshold."},{"id":"b","text":"Min and max heap (Xms/Xmx) should be set to the same value to avoid resize pauses."},{"id":"c","text":"Swapping should be disabled (e.g. bootstrap.memory_lock: true) for predictable performance."},{"id":"d","text":"Heap size is configured in elasticsearch.yml under index.heap."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a","b","c"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Heap is set via `jvm.options` (or JVM env), NOT `elasticsearch.yml`/`index.heap`. Best practice: Xms == Xmx, ≤ 50% RAM and under ~32 GB, and lock memory to avoid swapping.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/settings.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Configuring Elasticsearch"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Select ALL true statements about JVM heap and system configuration for an Elasticsearch node.$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Indexing Data$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which index setting CANNOT be changed after the index is created?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"number_of_replicas"},{"id":"b","text":"refresh_interval"},{"id":"c","text":"number_of_shards"},{"id":"d","text":"index.blocks.read_only"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["c"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`number_of_shards` (primary shard count) is fixed at creation; changing it requires reindex/split/shrink. Replicas, refresh interval, and blocks are dynamic settings updatable via `_settings`.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/indices-create-index.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Create index API"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which index setting CANNOT be changed after the index is created?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Indexing Data$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$You need to add a `processed: true` field to every document in `logs-*` that matches a query, in place. Which API does this?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"POST logs-*/_update_by_query with a script"},{"id":"b","text":"POST _reindex into the same index"},{"id":"c","text":"PUT logs-*/_mapping"},{"id":"d","text":"POST logs-*/_forcemerge"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`_update_by_query` runs a script over documents matching a query and updates them in place. Reindexing into the same index is unsafe; `_mapping` changes schema only; `_forcemerge` merges segments.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/docs-update-by-query.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Update By Query API"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$You need to add a `processed: true` field to every document in `logs-*` that matches a query, in place. Which API does this?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Indexing Data$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$An alias `orders` points to `orders-v1`. To switch readers to `orders-v2` atomically with zero downtime, you should:$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Delete the alias, then recreate it on orders-v2"},{"id":"b","text":"POST _aliases with one atomic action: remove orders from orders-v1 AND add it to orders-v2"},{"id":"c","text":"Rename orders-v1 to orders-v2"},{"id":"d","text":"Set orders-v1 read-only"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["b"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$The `_aliases` API applies multiple add/remove actions atomically in one request, enabling zero-downtime cutover. Delete-then-recreate leaves a window with no alias.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/aliases.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Aliases"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$An alias `orders` points to `orders-v1`. To switch readers to `orders-v2` atomically with zero downtime, you should:$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Indexing Data$tv2$, 4, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$In a `_bulk` request, one of 500 operations fails with a mapping conflict. What happens to the rest?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"The entire bulk request is rolled back."},{"id":"b","text":"Only the failing operation fails; the others succeed, and the response `errors` flag is true with per-item status."},{"id":"c","text":"All operations after the failing one are skipped."},{"id":"d","text":"The index is locked."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["b"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Bulk operations are independent. A failure affects only that item; the response has `errors: true` and a per-item `status`/`error`. There is no transactional rollback.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/docs-bulk.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Bulk API"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$In a `_bulk` request, one of 500 operations fails with a mapping conflict. What happens to the rest?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Queries$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$The key difference between query context and filter context is:$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Query context computes a relevance `_score`; filter context only answers yes/no and is cacheable."},{"id":"b","text":"Filter context computes a score; query context does not."},{"id":"c","text":"Both always compute a score."},{"id":"d","text":"Filter context can only be used on text fields."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$In query context a clause contributes to `_score` (how well it matches). In filter context the question is only "does it match?" — no scoring, and results are cacheable for speed.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/query-filter-context.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Query and filter context"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$The key difference between query context and filter context is:$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Queries$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which query finds documents with a numeric `age` between 18 and 30 inclusive?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"range query on age with gte:18, lte:30"},{"id":"b","text":"term query on age with value \"18-30\""},{"id":"c","text":"match query on age with \"18 30\""},{"id":"d","text":"exists query on age"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$The `range` query with `gte`/`lte` (or `gt`/`lt`) handles numeric and date ranges. `term`/`match` are not range operators; `exists` only checks presence.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/term-level-queries.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Term-level queries"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which query finds documents with a numeric `age` between 18 and 30 inclusive?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Queries$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$You want documents that MUST match `category:books`, SHOULD prefer `author:asimov`, and MUST NOT be `discontinued:true`. Which compound query expresses this?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"A `bool` query with `must` (category), `should` (author), and `must_not` (discontinued)"},{"id":"b","text":"A `dis_max` query"},{"id":"c","text":"A `constant_score` query"},{"id":"d","text":"A single `match` query with all conditions concatenated"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$The `bool` query composes `must`, `should`, `must_not`, and `filter` clauses — exactly mapping required, preferred, and excluded conditions.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/query-dsl-bool-query.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Boolean query"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$You want documents that MUST match `category:books`, SHOULD prefer `author:asimov`, and MUST NOT be `discontinued:true`. Which compound query expresses this?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Queries$tv2$, 4, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Relevance scoring in Elasticsearch by default uses which similarity algorithm?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"TF-IDF (classic Lucene)"},{"id":"b","text":"BM25 (Okapi BM25)"},{"id":"c","text":"PageRank"},{"id":"d","text":"Cosine similarity on raw term counts"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["b"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Since Lucene 6 / Elasticsearch 5, the default similarity is BM25, which improves on classic TF-IDF with term-frequency saturation and length normalization. PageRank/cosine are not the default text scoring model.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/query-dsl.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Query DSL"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Relevance scoring in Elasticsearch by default uses which similarity algorithm?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Mappings and Text Analysis$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which API lets you test how a specific analyzer tokenizes a piece of text WITHOUT indexing anything?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"GET _analyze (the Analyze API)"},{"id":"b","text":"GET _tokens"},{"id":"c","text":"POST _simulate/text"},{"id":"d","text":"GET _mapping/_test"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$The `_analyze` API returns the token stream produced by an analyzer (or a custom char_filter/tokenizer/filter chain) for given text, with no document indexed. The others are not real APIs for this.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/indices-analyze.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Analyze API"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which API lets you test how a specific analyzer tokenizes a piece of text WITHOUT indexing anything?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Mappings and Text Analysis$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$An analyzer in Elasticsearch is composed, in order, of:$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"tokenizer → char filters → token filters"},{"id":"b","text":"zero or more character filters → exactly one tokenizer → zero or more token filters"},{"id":"c","text":"one token filter → many tokenizers"},{"id":"d","text":"a mapping → a query → a result"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["b"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$An analyzer = optional character filter(s), then exactly ONE tokenizer, then optional token filter(s). Char filters preprocess raw text, the tokenizer splits into tokens, token filters modify the token stream (lowercase, stop, stemming).$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/analysis-custom-analyzer.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Create a custom analyzer"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$An analyzer in Elasticsearch is composed, in order, of:$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Mappings and Text Analysis$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$You define a custom analyzer with a `lowercase` token filter and an `html_strip` char filter. Which order is correct in the analysis chain?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"html_strip (char filter) runs first on raw text, then the tokenizer, then lowercase (token filter)"},{"id":"b","text":"lowercase runs first, then html_strip"},{"id":"c","text":"Both run after the tokenizer"},{"id":"d","text":"Char filters and token filters cannot be combined"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Character filters (e.g. `html_strip`) operate on the raw character stream BEFORE tokenization. Token filters (e.g. `lowercase`) operate on tokens AFTER the tokenizer. They are routinely combined in a custom analyzer.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/analysis-custom-analyzer.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Create a custom analyzer"},{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/analysis.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Text analysis"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$You define a custom analyzer with a `lowercase` token filter and an `html_strip` char filter. Which order is correct in the analysis chain?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Mappings and Text Analysis$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Once an index is created, changing the type of an existing field (e.g. `text` → `keyword`) requires:$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"A simple PUT _mapping update on the existing field"},{"id":"b","text":"Creating a new index with the corrected mapping and reindexing the data"},{"id":"c","text":"Restarting the cluster"},{"id":"d","text":"Setting dynamic: true"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["b"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$You cannot change the type of an existing mapped field in place. The standard procedure is to create a new index with the desired mapping and `_reindex` into it (often behind an alias for a clean cutover).$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/mapping.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Mapping"},{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/docs-reindex.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Reindex API"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Once an index is created, changing the type of an existing field (e.g. `text` → `keyword`) requires:$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Cluster Administration$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which feature automatically transitions indices through hot/warm/cold/delete phases based on age or size?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Index Lifecycle Management (ILM)"},{"id":"b","text":"Snapshot Lifecycle Management only"},{"id":"c","text":"Cross-cluster replication"},{"id":"d","text":"The reindex API on a schedule"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$ILM applies a policy with phases (hot, warm, cold, frozen, delete) and actions (rollover, shrink, force-merge, delete) based on age/size/doc count. SLM manages snapshots, not index phases.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/index-lifecycle-management.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Index lifecycle management"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which feature automatically transitions indices through hot/warm/cold/delete phases based on age or size?$tv2$);
