INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Mappings and Text Analysis$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which is the correct way to add a NEW field to an existing index mapping?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"PUT <index>/_mapping with the new field properties"},{"id":"b","text":"You must delete and recreate the index"},{"id":"c","text":"PUT <index>/_settings with the field"},{"id":"d","text":"It happens only via dynamic mapping; explicit addition is impossible"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$You CAN add new fields to an existing mapping with `PUT <index>/_mapping`. What you cannot do is change the type of an existing field. `_settings` is for index settings, not fields.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/mapping.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Mapping"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which is the correct way to add a NEW field to an existing index mapping?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Mappings and Text Analysis$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$The default analyzer applied to `text` fields when none is specified is:$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"the `standard` analyzer"},{"id":"b","text":"the `keyword` analyzer"},{"id":"c","text":"the `whitespace` analyzer"},{"id":"d","text":"no analyzer (text is stored verbatim)"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$The `standard` analyzer (standard tokenizer + lowercase token filter, Unicode-aware) is the default for `text` fields. `keyword` analyzer emits the whole input as one token; `whitespace` only splits on whitespace.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/analysis.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Text analysis"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$The default analyzer applied to `text` fields when none is specified is:$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Mappings and Text Analysis$tv2$, 3, $tv2$MULTI$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Select ALL true statements about Elasticsearch text analysis components.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"A tokenizer splits a character stream into tokens (e.g. the `standard` tokenizer)."},{"id":"b","text":"Token filters can add, remove, or modify tokens (e.g. `lowercase`, `stop`, `synonym`)."},{"id":"c","text":"Character filters operate on the token stream after tokenization."},{"id":"d","text":"A custom analyzer can combine char filters, one tokenizer, and multiple token filters."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a","b","d"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Character filters operate on the RAW character stream BEFORE tokenization, not after. Tokenizer splits into tokens; token filters transform them; a custom analyzer composes char filters + one tokenizer + token filters.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/analysis-custom-analyzer.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Create a custom analyzer"},{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/analysis.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Text analysis"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Select ALL true statements about Elasticsearch text analysis components.$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Mappings and Text Analysis$tv2$, 4, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$You map an analyzed `text` field but also need fast exact-match filtering on its raw value. The most storage-efficient idiomatic solution is:$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"A multi-field: text with a `.keyword` sub-field (type keyword, ignore_above)"},{"id":"b","text":"Two completely separate indices"},{"id":"c","text":"Enabling fielddata on the text field"},{"id":"d","text":"A separate runtime script field for every query"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$A multi-field indexes the same source both as `text` and `keyword` without duplicating the source field in your documents. Enabling fielddata on text is memory-heavy and discouraged for exact match/aggregations.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/multi-fields.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — multi-fields"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$You map an analyzed `text` field but also need fast exact-match filtering on its raw value. The most storage-efficient idiomatic solution is:$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Cluster Administration$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$A cluster health status of `red` indicates:$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"All shards allocated; cluster healthy."},{"id":"b","text":"At least one PRIMARY shard is not allocated — some data is unavailable."},{"id":"c","text":"Only replica shards are unassigned."},{"id":"d","text":"The cluster is performing a rolling upgrade."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["b"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Red means at least one primary shard is unassigned, so part of the data cannot be searched or indexed. Yellow = primaries OK but some replicas unassigned; green = all assigned.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/cluster-health.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Cluster health API"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$A cluster health status of `red` indicates:$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Cluster Administration$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$For querying indices that live on a SEPARATE remote Elasticsearch cluster without moving the data, you use:$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Cross-cluster search (configured remote clusters, query `remote:index`)"},{"id":"b","text":"A bigger single index"},{"id":"c","text":"Snapshot then restore on every query"},{"id":"d","text":"An ingest pipeline"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Cross-cluster search registers remote clusters and lets a local cluster query them with `<remote>:<index>` notation. Snapshots/ingest pipelines do not provide federated search.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/modules-cross-cluster-search.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Cross-cluster search"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$For querying indices that live on a SEPARATE remote Elasticsearch cluster without moving the data, you use:$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Data Processing and Aggregations$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which ingest processor would you use to copy/rename an incoming field to a new field name before indexing?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"The `rename` processor"},{"id":"b","text":"The `terms` aggregation"},{"id":"c","text":"The `reindex` API"},{"id":"d","text":"The `match` query"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$The `rename` ingest processor renames a field within the document during ingest. Aggregations/queries are search-time; reindex is a bulk copy API, not an in-pipeline transform.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/processors.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Ingest processor reference"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which ingest processor would you use to copy/rename an incoming field to a new field name before indexing?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Data Processing and Aggregations$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$You want average order value bucketed per day. The correct aggregation structure is:$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"A `date_histogram` bucket aggregation (calendar/fixed interval) with a nested `avg` metric sub-aggregation"},{"id":"b","text":"A single `avg` metric aggregation only"},{"id":"c","text":"A `terms` aggregation on the date field"},{"id":"d","text":"A pipeline aggregation with no parent"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Bucket per day = `date_histogram` (e.g. `calendar_interval: day`); the per-bucket average is a nested `avg` sub-aggregation. A bare `avg` gives one global number; `terms` on a raw date is not time-bucketed; pipeline aggs need a parent.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/search-aggregations.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Aggregations"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$You want average order value bucketed per day. The correct aggregation structure is:$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Installation and Configuration$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which directory does `path.logs` configure?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Where Elasticsearch writes its log files"},{"id":"b","text":"Where index data is stored"},{"id":"c","text":"Where snapshots are written"},{"id":"d","text":"The install root"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`path.logs` sets the log output directory. `path.data` is index data, `path.repo` is snapshot filesystem repos, and `path.home` (ES_HOME) is the install root.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/settings.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Configuring Elasticsearch"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which directory does `path.logs` configure?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Installation and Configuration$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which `node.roles` makes a node capable of running machine learning jobs?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"node.roles: [ ml ]"},{"id":"b","text":"node.roles: [ data_ml ]"},{"id":"c","text":"node.roles: [ analytics ]"},{"id":"d","text":"node.ml.enabled: true only"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$The `ml` role designates an ML node. There is no `data_ml`/`analytics` role; `xpack.ml.enabled` is a feature toggle, but the node role keyword in `node.roles` is `ml`.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/modules-node.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Node roles"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which `node.roles` makes a node capable of running machine learning jobs?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Installation and Configuration$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which `node.roles` value supports running transforms (pivoting data into entity-centric indices)?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"transform"},{"id":"b","text":"pivot"},{"id":"c","text":"data_transform"},{"id":"d","text":"aggregator"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$The `transform` role lets a node run transform jobs. `pivot` is a transform concept, not a role; `data_transform`/`aggregator` are not valid roles.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/modules-node.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Node roles"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which `node.roles` value supports running transforms (pivoting data into entity-centric indices)?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Installation and Configuration$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$After installing via the tar.gz archive, where do `elasticsearch.yml`, `jvm.options`, and `log4j2.properties` live by default?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"In the `config/` directory under ES_HOME"},{"id":"b","text":"In `/etc/elasticsearch` always"},{"id":"c","text":"In `path.data`"},{"id":"d","text":"In the JVM classpath only"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$For the archive distributions config files are in `$ES_HOME/config`. The package (RPM/DEB) installs place them in `/etc/elasticsearch`. They are never in `path.data`.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/settings.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Configuring Elasticsearch"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$After installing via the tar.gz archive, where do `elasticsearch.yml`, `jvm.options`, and `log4j2.properties` live by default?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Installation and Configuration$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which is true about file-realm vs native-realm users in Elasticsearch security?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"File realm users are defined in files on each node (managed with elasticsearch-users); native realm users are stored in a system index via the API"},{"id":"b","text":"Both are stored only in elasticsearch.yml"},{"id":"c","text":"Native realm users require LDAP"},{"id":"d","text":"File realm users are stored in the keystore"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$The file realm keeps users in node-local files (managed by `bin/elasticsearch-users`); the native realm stores users in a hidden security index, managed via the user-management APIs/Kibana. Neither lives in `elasticsearch.yml` or the keystore.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/configuring-stack-security.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Configure security"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which is true about file-realm vs native-realm users in Elasticsearch security?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Installation and Configuration$tv2$, 3, $tv2$TRUE_FALSE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$True or False: In Elasticsearch 8.x, basic authentication and TLS are part of the free Basic license.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"True"},{"id":"b","text":"False"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$True. Since 6.8/7.1 and continuing in 8.x, core security (TLS, native realm authentication, RBAC) is included in the free Basic license; advanced features (SSO, field-level security) need a paid tier.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/configuring-stack-security.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Configure security"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$True or False: In Elasticsearch 8.x, basic authentication and TLS are part of the free Basic license.$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Installation and Configuration$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which setting controls how long a node waits to find a master before logging warnings / failing health (cluster formation timeout-related)?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"cluster.election.* / discovery timeouts in the discovery module"},{"id":"b","text":"http.max_content_length"},{"id":"c","text":"index.refresh_interval"},{"id":"d","text":"thread_pool.write.size"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Discovery/election timeout settings (in the discovery module) govern master discovery/election behavior. `http.max_content_length`, `refresh_interval`, and thread pool sizing are unrelated to cluster formation.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/modules-discovery.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Discovery and cluster formation"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which setting controls how long a node waits to find a master before logging warnings / failing health (cluster formation timeout-related)?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Installation and Configuration$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$A dedicated master node should generally NOT also be a data node because:$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Heavy data/query load can destabilize the master and risk cluster stability"},{"id":"b","text":"Master nodes cannot store any settings"},{"id":"c","text":"It is forbidden by the API"},{"id":"d","text":"Data nodes cannot vote"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Separating master-eligible nodes from data load keeps the cluster-coordination function stable under heavy indexing/search. It is allowed (small clusters combine roles) but discouraged at scale.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/modules-node.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Node roles"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$A dedicated master node should generally NOT also be a data node because:$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Installation and Configuration$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which command-line tool can be used to safely remove a node's persisted cluster metadata for unsafe recovery scenarios?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"bin/elasticsearch-node"},{"id":"b","text":"bin/elasticsearch-keystore"},{"id":"c","text":"bin/elasticsearch-certutil"},{"id":"d","text":"bin/elasticsearch-sql-cli"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$The `elasticsearch-node` tool provides unsafe cluster bootstrap/detach/repair subcommands. `keystore` handles secrets, `certutil` certs, and `sql-cli` is the SQL client.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/settings.html","label":"Elasticsearch Reference — Configuring Elasticsearch"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:elastic-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$elastic-certified-engineer-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which command-line tool can be used to safely remove a node's persisted cluster metadata for unsafe recovery scenarios?$tv2$);
