INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Use Terraform Outside the Core Workflow$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$You want to retrieve only the value of a single root output named `endpoint` for a shell script. Which command?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"terraform output -raw endpoint"},{"id":"b","text":"terraform show endpoint"},{"id":"c","text":"terraform get endpoint"},{"id":"d","text":"terraform console endpoint"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`terraform output -raw endpoint` prints just the string value of that output, ideal for scripting. `show`/`get`/`console` do not retrieve a single output that way.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/output","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform output"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$You want to retrieve only the value of a single root output named `endpoint` for a shell script. Which command?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Implement and Maintain State$tv2$, 1, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$What is the default local state file name?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"state.json"},{"id":"b","text":"terraform.tfstate"},{"id":"c","text":"tfstate.lock"},{"id":"d","text":".terraform"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["b"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$The local backend writes `terraform.tfstate` (with a `terraform.tfstate.backup` previous copy). `.terraform` is the plugin/module directory, not state.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/state","label":"Terraform Docs — State"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$What is the default local state file name?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Implement and Maintain State$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which command switches the active workspace to an existing one named "prod"?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"terraform workspace select prod"},{"id":"b","text":"terraform workspace new prod"},{"id":"c","text":"terraform workspace switch prod"},{"id":"d","text":"terraform select workspace prod"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`terraform workspace select <name>` switches to an existing workspace; `new` would create one. `switch` and the last form are not valid.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/state/workspaces","label":"Terraform Docs — Workspaces"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which command switches the active workspace to an existing one named "prod"?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Implement and Maintain State$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$A backend block is added for the first time to a config that already has local state. What does `terraform init` offer?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"To migrate the existing local state into the new backend."},{"id":"b","text":"To delete the local state silently."},{"id":"c","text":"To ignore the backend until next apply."},{"id":"d","text":"Nothing — backends cannot be added later."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$When a backend is added/changed, `terraform init` prompts to migrate existing state into the new backend. Backends can be added later; state is not silently deleted.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/init","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform init"},{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/backend","label":"Terraform Docs — Backends"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$A backend block is added for the first time to a config that already has local state. What does `terraform init` offer?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Implement and Maintain State$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which backend is purpose-built to provide managed remote state, remote runs, and locking as a service?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"The local backend."},{"id":"b","text":"HCP Terraform (Terraform Cloud) / `cloud` block."},{"id":"c","text":"The `terraform.tfvars` file."},{"id":"d","text":"The `.terraform` directory."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["b"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$HCP Terraform (configured via the `cloud` block or `remote` backend) provides managed state, remote operations, and locking. The local backend stores state on disk only.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/cloud","label":"Terraform Docs — HCP Terraform"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which backend is purpose-built to provide managed remote state, remote runs, and locking as a service?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Implement and Maintain State$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Two engineers share an S3 backend with a DynamoDB lock table. Engineer A is mid-apply. What happens when Engineer B runs apply?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"B's apply proceeds in parallel, risking corruption."},{"id":"b","text":"B is blocked/errors with a state lock until A's operation completes."},{"id":"c","text":"B overwrites A's state immediately."},{"id":"d","text":"B's apply is queued for one hour automatically."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["b"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$With locking, B cannot acquire the state lock while A holds it, so B's operation fails fast or waits rather than corrupting state. There is no automatic one-hour queue.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/state/locking","label":"Terraform Docs — State Locking"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Two engineers share an S3 backend with a DynamoDB lock table. Engineer A is mid-apply. What happens when Engineer B runs apply?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Implement and Maintain State$tv2$, 2, $tv2$TRUE_FALSE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$True or False: Each Terraform CLI workspace maintains its own distinct state while sharing the same configuration and backend.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"True"},{"id":"b","text":"False"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$True. Workspaces give multiple isolated states for one configuration/backend, enabling parallel environments without copying code.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/state/workspaces","label":"Terraform Docs — Workspaces"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$True or False: Each Terraform CLI workspace maintains its own distinct state while sharing the same configuration and backend.$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Implement and Maintain State$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$You accidentally deleted a resource from configuration and ran apply, destroying it, but want it back without recreating from scratch — what would have prevented this destroy?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"A `lifecycle { prevent_destroy = true }` on the resource."},{"id":"b","text":"Setting `sensitive = true` on an output."},{"id":"c","text":"Adding `depends_on`."},{"id":"d","text":"Running `terraform fmt` first."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`prevent_destroy = true` makes Terraform reject any plan that would destroy that resource, guarding critical infrastructure. The other options do not block destruction.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/meta-arguments/lifecycle","label":"Terraform Docs — lifecycle"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$You accidentally deleted a resource from configuration and ran apply, destroying it, but want it back without recreating from scratch — what would have prevented this destroy?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Read, Generate, and Modify Configuration$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which expression accesses a value from a map variable `tags` at key "Name"?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"var.tags[\"Name\"]"},{"id":"b","text":"var.tags.Name()"},{"id":"c","text":"tags::Name"},{"id":"d","text":"var[Name].tags"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Map values are read with bracket (or dot) syntax: `var.tags["Name"]`. The other forms are not valid HCL expressions.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/expressions","label":"Terraform Docs — Expressions"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which expression accesses a value from a map variable `tags` at key "Name"?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Read, Generate, and Modify Configuration$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which construct best avoids repeating the same complex expression in several places within one module?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"A `locals` value referenced as `local.<name>`."},{"id":"b","text":"A `provisioner`."},{"id":"c","text":"A second `provider` block."},{"id":"d","text":"A `backend` block."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Local values name a computed expression once and reuse it via `local.<name>`, keeping configuration DRY. Provisioners, providers, and backends serve different purposes.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/values/locals","label":"Terraform Docs — Local Values"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which construct best avoids repeating the same complex expression in several places within one module?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Read, Generate, and Modify Configuration$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which interpolation correctly embeds a variable into a string?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"\"web-${var.env}\""},{"id":"b","text":"\"web-$var.env\""},{"id":"c","text":"\"web-{{var.env}}\""},{"id":"d","text":"\"web-#var.env#\""}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$HCL string interpolation uses `${ ... }`, e.g. `"web-${var.env}"`. The other syntaxes are not valid Terraform interpolation.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/expressions","label":"Terraform Docs — Expressions"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which interpolation correctly embeds a variable into a string?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Read, Generate, and Modify Configuration$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$You want to transform a list of names into a map keyed by name. Which expression style does this?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"A `for` expression producing a map: `{ for n in var.names : n => upper(n) }`."},{"id":"b","text":"A `count` meta-argument."},{"id":"c","text":"A `provisioner` block."},{"id":"d","text":"A `terraform_remote_state` data source."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$A `for` expression with `key => value` syntax builds a map from a collection. count multiplies resources, provisioners run scripts, and remote_state reads other state.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/expressions","label":"Terraform Docs — Expressions"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$You want to transform a list of names into a map keyed by name. Which expression style does this?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Read, Generate, and Modify Configuration$tv2$, 2, $tv2$TRUE_FALSE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$True or False: Marking an input variable `sensitive = true` causes Terraform to redact its value from plan/apply CLI output.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"True"},{"id":"b","text":"False"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$True. A `sensitive` variable (or output) is redacted in CLI output, though its value is still stored in state and used during operations.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/values/variables","label":"Terraform Docs — Input Variables"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p2$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$True or False: Marking an input variable `sensitive = true` causes Terraform to redact its value from plan/apply CLI output.$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Infrastructure as Code (IaC) Concepts$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$What is "configuration drift" in the context of IaC?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"When the Terraform binary version differs from the provider version."},{"id":"b","text":"When the real infrastructure no longer matches the state/configuration because of out-of-band changes."},{"id":"c","text":"When two modules use the same variable name."},{"id":"d","text":"When the plan output is longer than the apply output."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["b"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Drift is when actual infrastructure diverges from what Terraform expects (recorded in state/config), usually due to manual changes. Version mismatches and naming overlaps are different concerns.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/state","label":"Terraform Docs — State"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$What is "configuration drift" in the context of IaC?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Infrastructure as Code (IaC) Concepts$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which practice is MOST aligned with the IaC principle of idempotence?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Re-applying the same configuration repeatedly results in the same end state with no unintended changes."},{"id":"b","text":"Each apply creates brand-new duplicate resources."},{"id":"c","text":"Manual hotfixes are applied directly in the console."},{"id":"d","text":"Configuration files are deleted after every apply."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Idempotence means applying the same desired-state configuration repeatedly converges to the same result without spurious changes. Duplicating resources or manual hotfixes break that property.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/intro","label":"Terraform Docs — Infrastructure as Code"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which practice is MOST aligned with the IaC principle of idempotence?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$The Purpose of Terraform (vs other IaC)$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which scenario is a strong use case for Terraform specifically (rather than a config-management tool)?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Installing and patching nginx inside 500 already-running servers."},{"id":"b","text":"Provisioning a multi-cloud landing zone: VPCs, subnets, load balancers, and managed databases."},{"id":"c","text":"Tailing application logs in real time."},{"id":"d","text":"Running unit tests for an application."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["b"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Provisioning and wiring cloud infrastructure across providers is Terraform's core use case. In-server software install/patching is configuration management; logging and unit tests are unrelated.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/intro/use-cases","label":"Terraform Docs — Use Cases"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which scenario is a strong use case for Terraform specifically (rather than a config-management tool)?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$The Purpose of Terraform (vs other IaC)$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$HCP Terraform / Terraform Cloud adds which capability beyond the open-source CLI for the purpose of safe team collaboration?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Remote state storage with remote runs, access controls, and a private module registry."},{"id":"b","text":"The ability to write configuration in HCL."},{"id":"c","text":"Support for the `terraform plan` command."},{"id":"d","text":"The provider plugin architecture."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$HCP Terraform adds managed remote state, remote operations, RBAC, policy, and a private registry for team workflows. HCL, `plan`, and the provider model are part of the open-source CLI itself.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/cloud","label":"Terraform Docs — HCP Terraform"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$HCP Terraform / Terraform Cloud adds which capability beyond the open-source CLI for the purpose of safe team collaboration?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Terraform Fundamentals$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which command rewrites Terraform configuration files to the canonical HCL style/format?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"terraform fmt"},{"id":"b","text":"terraform style"},{"id":"c","text":"terraform lint"},{"id":"d","text":"terraform validate"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`terraform fmt` rewrites `.tf` files to the canonical format. `terraform validate` checks syntax/consistency but does not reformat; `style` and `lint` are not Terraform subcommands.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/fmt","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform fmt"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which command rewrites Terraform configuration files to the canonical HCL style/format?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Terraform Fundamentals$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$What does `terraform validate` check?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Whether the configuration is syntactically valid and internally consistent, without contacting any provider/remote API."},{"id":"b","text":"Whether the real cloud resources still exist."},{"id":"c","text":"Whether the state file is locked."},{"id":"d","text":"Whether your cloud credentials are valid."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`terraform validate` checks configuration syntax and internal consistency in an initialized directory; it does not access remote state, real resources, or credentials.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/validate","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform validate"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$What does `terraform validate` check?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Terraform Fundamentals$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$You configure two instances of the AWS provider for different regions. Which feature lets a resource choose the non-default provider instance?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Provider `alias` plus the resource's `provider` meta-argument (e.g. provider = aws.west)."},{"id":"b","text":"A separate backend block per region."},{"id":"c","text":"Two `terraform` settings blocks."},{"id":"d","text":"The `count` meta-argument."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Multiple provider configurations use `alias`; a resource selects one via the `provider = <name>.<alias>` meta-argument. Backends and the terraform block are unrelated; count just multiplies instances.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/providers","label":"Terraform Docs — Providers"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$You configure two instances of the AWS provider for different regions. Which feature lets a resource choose the non-default provider instance?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$The Terraform Workflow$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$During `terraform plan`, a resource shows the symbol `-/+`. What does this indicate?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"The resource will be created only."},{"id":"b","text":"The resource will be destroyed and then re-created (replacement)."},{"id":"c","text":"The resource will be left unchanged."},{"id":"d","text":"The resource will be imported."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["b"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$In plan output, `-/+` means destroy then create (replacement). `+` is create, `~` is update in place, `-` is destroy, and unchanged resources are not shown.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/plan","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform plan"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$During `terraform plan`, a resource shows the symbol `-/+`. What does this indicate?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$The Terraform Workflow$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$You changed only one resource and want to limit the plan/apply to that resource (use sparingly). Which flag does this?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"-target=\"aws_instance.web\""},{"id":"b","text":"-only=\"aws_instance.web\""},{"id":"c","text":"-resource=\"aws_instance.web\""},{"id":"d","text":"-scope=\"aws_instance.web\""}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$The `-target=ADDR` flag restricts operations to the specified resource (and its dependencies). It is intended for exceptional use. The other flags do not exist.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/plan","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform plan"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$You changed only one resource and want to limit the plan/apply to that resource (use sparingly). Which flag does this?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$The Terraform Workflow$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$After editing `backend` configuration in the `terraform` block, what must you do before plan/apply works again?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Run `terraform init` (Terraform will prompt to migrate/reconfigure the backend)."},{"id":"b","text":"Run `terraform fmt`."},{"id":"c","text":"Delete the state file manually."},{"id":"d","text":"Nothing — backend changes take effect automatically."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Backend changes require re-running `terraform init`, which prompts to migrate or reconfigure state. Backend changes are NOT picked up automatically, and deleting state is unsafe.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/init","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform init"},{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/backend","label":"Terraform Docs — Backends"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$After editing `backend` configuration in the `terraform` block, what must you do before plan/apply works again?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Terraform Modules$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$After adding a new `module` block that sources a registry module, which command must you run before `plan`?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"terraform get or terraform init (to install the module)."},{"id":"b","text":"terraform fmt"},{"id":"c","text":"terraform console"},{"id":"d","text":"terraform output"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$New/changed modules must be installed via `terraform init` (or `terraform get`) before planning. fmt, console, and output do not install modules.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/modules","label":"Terraform Docs — Modules"},{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/init","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform init"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$After adding a new `module` block that sources a registry module, which command must you run before `plan`?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Terraform Modules$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$A child module declares `variable "name" {}` with no default. What happens if the calling `module` block does not set `name`?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Terraform uses an empty string automatically."},{"id":"b","text":"Terraform errors because a required input variable is not set."},{"id":"c","text":"Terraform ignores the variable."},{"id":"d","text":"Terraform prompts for it only during destroy."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["b"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$A variable with no `default` is required; omitting it for a child module causes an error (child module variables cannot be supplied interactively). A missing default does not become an empty string.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/values/variables","label":"Terraform Docs — Input Variables"},{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/modules","label":"Terraform Docs — Modules"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$A child module declares `variable "name" {}` with no default. What happens if the calling `module` block does not set `name`?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Terraform Modules$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$You want to deploy three near-identical environments from one module. Which meta-argument on the `module` block creates multiple instances keyed by a map?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"for_each"},{"id":"b","text":"depends_on"},{"id":"c","text":"provider"},{"id":"d","text":"lifecycle"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`for_each` on a module block instantiates the module once per map/set element, keyed by the element key. `depends_on` only orders, `provider` passes providers, and `lifecycle` is not a module-block meta-argument.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/meta-arguments/for_each","label":"Terraform Docs — for_each"},{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/modules","label":"Terraform Docs — Modules"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$You want to deploy three near-identical environments from one module. Which meta-argument on the `module` block creates multiple instances keyed by a map?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Use Terraform Outside the Core Workflow$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which command prints the values of the root module's output variables from current state?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"terraform output"},{"id":"b","text":"terraform show outputs"},{"id":"c","text":"terraform console -output"},{"id":"d","text":"terraform get output"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`terraform output` reads root output values from state and can emit a specific one or JSON. The other invocations are not valid commands for this purpose.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/output","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform output"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which command prints the values of the root module's output variables from current state?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Use Terraform Outside the Core Workflow$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$One configuration needs to consume outputs produced by ANOTHER configuration's remote state. Which data source enables this?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"data \"terraform_remote_state\""},{"id":"b","text":"data \"external\""},{"id":"c","text":"data \"local_file\""},{"id":"d","text":"resource \"terraform_state\""}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$The `terraform_remote_state` data source reads outputs from another configuration's state backend. `external` runs an external program, `local_file` reads a file, and `terraform_state` is not a resource.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/state/remote-state-data","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform_remote_state"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$One configuration needs to consume outputs produced by ANOTHER configuration's remote state. Which data source enables this?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Implement and Maintain State$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which statement about Terraform CLI workspaces is correct?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Each workspace has its own separate state, but they share the same configuration."},{"id":"b","text":"Workspaces store separate provider plugins."},{"id":"c","text":"Workspaces are the same as Git branches."},{"id":"d","text":"Workspaces require a different backend per workspace."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$CLI workspaces provide multiple named states for the same configuration/backend, enabling parallel environments. They are not Git branches and do not duplicate plugins or backends.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/state/workspaces","label":"Terraform Docs — Workspaces"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which statement about Terraform CLI workspaces is correct?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Implement and Maintain State$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$A resource was renamed in configuration (its address changed). Which command moves the existing object in state to the new address WITHOUT destroying it?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"terraform state mv OLD_ADDR NEW_ADDR"},{"id":"b","text":"terraform import NEW_ADDR"},{"id":"c","text":"terraform apply -replace=OLD_ADDR"},{"id":"d","text":"terraform refresh"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`terraform state mv` re-keys an existing object to a new address, avoiding destroy/recreate. Import would create a duplicate-state tracking, replace recreates, and refresh only syncs.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/state","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform state"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$A resource was renamed in configuration (its address changed). Which command moves the existing object in state to the new address WITHOUT destroying it?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Implement and Maintain State$tv2$, 3, $tv2$MULTI$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Select ALL true statements about Terraform state.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"State may contain sensitive values (e.g. passwords) and should be stored securely."},{"id":"b","text":"Manually hand-editing the state JSON is discouraged in favor of `terraform state` commands."},{"id":"c","text":"A remote backend can enable state locking to prevent concurrent corrupting writes."},{"id":"d","text":"State is optional and Terraform can always rebuild it for free with no risk."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a","b","c"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$State can hold secrets, should be edited via `terraform state` (not by hand), and remote backends can lock it. State is essential — losing or carelessly rebuilding it risks orphaned/destroyed resources.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/state","label":"Terraform Docs — State"},{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/state","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform state"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Select ALL true statements about Terraform state.$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Read, Generate, and Modify Configuration$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$You need to create N identical subnets where N comes from a variable. Which meta-argument is the simplest fit?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"count = var.subnet_count"},{"id":"b","text":"depends_on = var.subnet_count"},{"id":"c","text":"provider = var.subnet_count"},{"id":"d","text":"lifecycle = var.subnet_count"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`count` creates a fixed number of near-identical instances of a resource indexed numerically. `depends_on` orders, `provider` selects a provider, and `lifecycle` is a nested block, not a numeric multiplier.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/meta-arguments/count","label":"Terraform Docs — count"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$You need to create N identical subnets where N comes from a variable. Which meta-argument is the simplest fit?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Read, Generate, and Modify Configuration$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$You want to prevent Terraform from accidentally destroying a critical database resource. Which configuration achieves this?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"A `lifecycle` block with `prevent_destroy = true` on the resource."},{"id":"b","text":"Setting `count = 0` on the resource."},{"id":"c","text":"Adding `depends_on = []`."},{"id":"d","text":"Marking the resource output as `sensitive = true`."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`lifecycle { prevent_destroy = true }` makes Terraform reject any plan that would destroy the resource. `count = 0` would actually remove it, depends_on orders dependencies, and sensitive only hides output values.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/meta-arguments/lifecycle","label":"Terraform Docs — lifecycle"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$You want to prevent Terraform from accidentally destroying a critical database resource. Which configuration achieves this?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Infrastructure as Code (IaC) Concepts$tv2$, 1, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which best describes a key reason organizations adopt IaC?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"To make every change require a manual ticket and console session."},{"id":"b","text":"To automate provisioning so environments are consistent and quickly reproducible."},{"id":"c","text":"To stop tracking what infrastructure exists."},{"id":"d","text":"To remove the need for cloud accounts."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["b"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$IaC automates provisioning for consistent, fast, reproducible environments. It does not require manual tickets, stop tracking infrastructure, or remove cloud accounts.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/intro","label":"Terraform Docs — Infrastructure as Code"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which best describes a key reason organizations adopt IaC?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Infrastructure as Code (IaC) Concepts$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$A team scales from one environment to ten using the same parameterized configuration. Which IaC property is demonstrated?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Reproducibility / repeatability."},{"id":"b","text":"Statelessness."},{"id":"c","text":"Manual provisioning."},{"id":"d","text":"Vendor lock-in."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Recreating many consistent environments from one parameterized configuration illustrates reproducibility/repeatability, a central IaC benefit.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/intro","label":"Terraform Docs — Infrastructure as Code"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$A team scales from one environment to ten using the same parameterized configuration. Which IaC property is demonstrated?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Infrastructure as Code (IaC) Concepts$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Why is "self-service" infrastructure often cited as an IaC benefit?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Teams can provision approved, codified infrastructure via a repeatable pipeline instead of ticketing ops manually."},{"id":"b","text":"It removes the need for any approvals ever."},{"id":"c","text":"It deletes infrastructure automatically every night."},{"id":"d","text":"It bypasses provider APIs."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Codified, reviewed infrastructure can be offered through automated pipelines, enabling safe self-service. It does not abolish approvals or bypass provider APIs.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/intro/use-cases","label":"Terraform Docs — Use Cases"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Why is "self-service" infrastructure often cited as an IaC benefit?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Infrastructure as Code (IaC) Concepts$tv2$, 3, $tv2$MULTI$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Select ALL accurate statements about Infrastructure as Code.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Configuration can be peer-reviewed before being applied."},{"id":"b","text":"The same code can build identical environments repeatedly."},{"id":"c","text":"Changes have a tracked history in version control."},{"id":"d","text":"IaC removes the need to ever test changes."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a","b","c"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$IaC enables review, repeatable builds, and change history. It does not remove the need to test — previewing/validating changes is still important.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/intro","label":"Terraform Docs — Infrastructure as Code"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Select ALL accurate statements about Infrastructure as Code.$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$The Purpose of Terraform (vs other IaC)$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which best explains why Terraform keeps state rather than querying the cloud every time?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"State stores credentials so APIs are unnecessary."},{"id":"b","text":"State records the mapping of configuration to real resources and metadata, enabling accurate, performant plans."},{"id":"c","text":"State replaces the configuration files."},{"id":"d","text":"State is only used by HCP Terraform."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["b"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$State maps config to real objects and stores metadata so Terraform can compute accurate plans efficiently. It is not a credential store, a config replacement, or HCP-only.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/state","label":"Terraform Docs — State"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which best explains why Terraform keeps state rather than querying the cloud every time?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$The Purpose of Terraform (vs other IaC)$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$For team collaboration, which HCP Terraform capability most directly reduces the risk of conflicting concurrent changes?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Managed remote state with locking and remote runs."},{"id":"b","text":"Syntax highlighting in the editor."},{"id":"c","text":"The ability to write HCL."},{"id":"d","text":"Local-only state files."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Managed remote state with locking and serialized remote runs prevents conflicting concurrent applies. HCL and editor features do not address concurrency; local state makes it worse.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/cloud","label":"Terraform Docs — HCP Terraform"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$For team collaboration, which HCP Terraform capability most directly reduces the risk of conflicting concurrent changes?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$The Purpose of Terraform (vs other IaC)$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Terraform vs CloudFormation: which statement is accurate about Terraform's purpose?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Terraform is multi-cloud via providers, not limited to a single vendor's services."},{"id":"b","text":"Terraform only manages AWS resources."},{"id":"c","text":"Terraform cannot manage SaaS or Kubernetes."},{"id":"d","text":"Terraform compiles to CloudFormation templates."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Terraform is provider-driven and works across many clouds and platforms (including Kubernetes and SaaS), unlike a single-vendor tool. It does not compile to CloudFormation.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/providers","label":"Terraform Docs — Providers"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Terraform vs CloudFormation: which statement is accurate about Terraform's purpose?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$The Purpose of Terraform (vs other IaC)$tv2$, 2, $tv2$TRUE_FALSE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$True or False: A core purpose of Terraform is to provide a predictable plan/apply workflow that previews changes before they are made.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"True"},{"id":"b","text":"False"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$True. The plan-then-apply model giving a predictable preview of changes is central to Terraform's value proposition.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/plan","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform plan"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$True or False: A core purpose of Terraform is to provide a predictable plan/apply workflow that previews changes before they are made.$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Terraform Fundamentals$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which command checks configuration syntax/consistency but does not require provider credentials or network access?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"terraform validate"},{"id":"b","text":"terraform apply"},{"id":"c","text":"terraform import"},{"id":"d","text":"terraform refresh"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`terraform validate` checks syntax and internal consistency offline in an initialized directory. apply/import/refresh contact providers or modify state.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/validate","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform validate"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which command checks configuration syntax/consistency but does not require provider credentials or network access?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Terraform Fundamentals$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which file typically declares variables (their names, types, defaults) by convention?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"variables.tf"},{"id":"b","text":"terraform.tfstate"},{"id":"c","text":".terraform.lock.hcl"},{"id":"d","text":"backend.json"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$By convention `variables.tf` holds `variable` declarations (Terraform actually loads all `.tf` files). The lock file and state file serve different roles.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/values/variables","label":"Terraform Docs — Input Variables"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which file typically declares variables (their names, types, defaults) by convention?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Terraform Fundamentals$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which environment variable form sets the Terraform input variable `db_password`?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"TF_VAR_db_password"},{"id":"b","text":"TERRAFORM_db_password"},{"id":"c","text":"VAR_db_password"},{"id":"d","text":"TF_db_password"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Terraform reads `TF_VAR_<name>` environment variables to set input variables, e.g. `TF_VAR_db_password`. The other prefixes are not recognized.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/values/variables","label":"Terraform Docs — Input Variables"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which environment variable form sets the Terraform input variable `db_password`?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Terraform Fundamentals$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$What does `terraform fmt -recursive` do?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Formats `.tf` files in the current directory and all subdirectories."},{"id":"b","text":"Validates all modules recursively."},{"id":"c","text":"Destroys nested resources."},{"id":"d","text":"Initializes every submodule's backend."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`terraform fmt -recursive` reformats configuration files in the current directory and all subdirectories. It does not validate, destroy, or init.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/fmt","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform fmt"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$What does `terraform fmt -recursive` do?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Terraform Fundamentals$tv2$, 1, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which block exposes a value (like an instance IP) for users or other configurations to read?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"output"},{"id":"b","text":"variable"},{"id":"c","text":"provider"},{"id":"d","text":"backend"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$An `output` block surfaces a value after apply (and for `terraform output`/remote_state). variables are inputs, provider configures the platform, backend stores state.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/values/outputs","label":"Terraform Docs — Output Values"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which block exposes a value (like an instance IP) for users or other configurations to read?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Terraform Fundamentals$tv2$, 3, $tv2$MULTI$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Select ALL true statements about provider version constraints.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"`= 3.1.0` pins an exact version."},{"id":"b","text":"`>= 3.1.0` allows that version or newer."},{"id":"c","text":"`~> 3.1` allows 3.x but not 4.0."},{"id":"d","text":"Version constraints are stored in the state file."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a","b","c"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Exact, lower-bound, and pessimistic constraints behave as described. Version constraints live in configuration (`required_providers`) and selections in the lock file — not in state.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/settings","label":"Terraform Docs — Terraform Settings"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Select ALL true statements about provider version constraints.$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Terraform Fundamentals$tv2$, 2, $tv2$TRUE_FALSE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$True or False: `terraform validate` requires the working directory to have been initialized first with `terraform init`.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"True"},{"id":"b","text":"False"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$True. `validate` needs provider schemas/modules available, so the directory must be initialized via `terraform init` first.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/validate","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform validate"},{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/init","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform init"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$True or False: `terraform validate` requires the working directory to have been initialized first with `terraform init`.$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$The Terraform Workflow$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$What does a `-` (minus) prefix on a resource in plan output indicate?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"It will be created."},{"id":"b","text":"It will be destroyed."},{"id":"c","text":"It will be updated in place."},{"id":"d","text":"It is unchanged."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["b"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`-` means the resource will be destroyed; `+` create, `~` update in place, `-/+` replace.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/plan","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform plan"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$What does a `-` (minus) prefix on a resource in plan output indicate?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$The Terraform Workflow$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which command would you add to a CI pipeline to fail the build if files are not canonically formatted?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"terraform fmt -check"},{"id":"b","text":"terraform fmt -write"},{"id":"c","text":"terraform validate -fmt"},{"id":"d","text":"terraform plan -fmt"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`terraform fmt -check` exits non-zero if any file is not properly formatted, without rewriting — ideal for CI gating. The other forms do not perform this check.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/fmt","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform fmt"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which command would you add to a CI pipeline to fail the build if files are not canonically formatted?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$The Terraform Workflow$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$You need to recreate one resource on the next apply because the provider cannot detect a needed change. Current recommended command?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"terraform apply -replace=\"aws_db_instance.main\""},{"id":"b","text":"terraform taint aws_db_instance.main"},{"id":"c","text":"terraform refresh"},{"id":"d","text":"terraform fmt"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`terraform apply -replace=ADDR` is the modern recommended way to force replacement of a specific resource; `terraform taint` is deprecated. refresh/fmt do not recreate.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/apply","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform apply"},{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/taint","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform taint"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$You need to recreate one resource on the next apply because the provider cannot detect a needed change. Current recommended command?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$The Terraform Workflow$tv2$, 1, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$In the core workflow, which step actually changes real infrastructure?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Write"},{"id":"b","text":"Plan"},{"id":"c","text":"Apply"},{"id":"d","text":"Validate"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["c"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Apply executes the planned changes against real infrastructure. Write authors config, Plan previews, and Validate checks syntax.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/apply","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform apply"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$In the core workflow, which step actually changes real infrastructure?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$The Terraform Workflow$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Why is `-target` documented as something to use sparingly?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"It permanently disables state."},{"id":"b","text":"It can produce a partial apply that diverges from full configuration, so it is for exceptional cases."},{"id":"c","text":"It deletes the lock file."},{"id":"d","text":"It always destroys all resources."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["b"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`-target` applies only a subset, which can leave configuration and state inconsistent if overused; it is meant for exceptional recovery situations, not routine use.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/plan","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform plan"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Why is `-target` documented as something to use sparingly?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$The Terraform Workflow$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$You changed the `backend` block. Running `terraform plan` immediately gives a backend initialization error. What is the fix?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Re-run `terraform init` to migrate/reconfigure the backend."},{"id":"b","text":"Run `terraform fmt`."},{"id":"c","text":"Delete `.terraform.lock.hcl`."},{"id":"d","text":"Run `terraform output`."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Backend changes require `terraform init` (often with `-migrate-state` or `-reconfigure`) before plan/apply works again. fmt/output and deleting the lock file do not resolve it.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/init","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform init"},{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/backend","label":"Terraform Docs — Backends"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$You changed the `backend` block. Running `terraform plan` immediately gives a backend initialization error. What is the fix?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$The Terraform Workflow$tv2$, 2, $tv2$MULTI$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Select ALL commands that are read-only with respect to real infrastructure.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"terraform plan"},{"id":"b","text":"terraform validate"},{"id":"c","text":"terraform fmt"},{"id":"d","text":"terraform destroy"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a","b","c"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$plan previews, validate checks syntax, and fmt formats files — none change real infrastructure. destroy removes resources.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/plan","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform plan"},{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/validate","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform validate"},{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/fmt","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform fmt"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Select ALL commands that are read-only with respect to real infrastructure.$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Terraform Modules$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$A module on the public registry is referenced without a host prefix. Which registry is implied?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"The public Terraform Registry (registry.terraform.io)."},{"id":"b","text":"A private GitLab instance."},{"id":"c","text":"The local filesystem."},{"id":"d","text":"An S3 bucket."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$A bare `<namespace>/<name>/<provider>` address resolves to the public Terraform Registry by default; other hosts need an explicit host prefix.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/modules/syntax","label":"Terraform Docs — Module Registry"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$A module on the public registry is referenced without a host prefix. Which registry is implied?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Terraform Modules$tv2$, 1, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which keyword/block calls a child module from the root configuration?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"module"},{"id":"b","text":"resource"},{"id":"c","text":"provider"},{"id":"d","text":"data"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$A `module` block instantiates a child module (with `source` and inputs). resource/data/provider declare other constructs.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/modules","label":"Terraform Docs — Modules"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which keyword/block calls a child module from the root configuration?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Terraform Modules$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which is true about outputs declared in a child module?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"They are only consumable by the calling configuration via `module.<name>.<output>`."},{"id":"b","text":"They are global variables anywhere in the project."},{"id":"c","text":"They are written to the provider plugin."},{"id":"d","text":"They cannot reference the module's own resources."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Child module outputs are exposed to the caller as `module.<name>.<output>` and typically reference the module's resources. They are not global or written to plugins.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/values/outputs","label":"Terraform Docs — Output Values"},{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/modules","label":"Terraform Docs — Modules"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which is true about outputs declared in a child module?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Terraform Modules$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$A module needs an aliased provider configured in the root. How is it passed to the child module?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Via the `providers = { aws = aws.west }` argument in the `module` block."},{"id":"b","text":"By redeclaring the provider inside the child automatically."},{"id":"c","text":"Through an `output` block."},{"id":"d","text":"It is impossible to pass aliased providers to modules."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$The `providers` meta-argument on a `module` block maps the caller's (possibly aliased) provider configurations into the child module. Outputs are unrelated to provider passing.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/providers","label":"Terraform Docs — Providers"},{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/modules","label":"Terraform Docs — Modules"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$A module needs an aliased provider configured in the root. How is it passed to the child module?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Terraform Modules$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$What happens if you change a registry module's pinned `version` and run plan without re-initializing?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Terraform errors/asks you to run init because the new module version is not installed."},{"id":"b","text":"Terraform silently downloads it during plan."},{"id":"c","text":"Terraform ignores the version change."},{"id":"d","text":"Terraform destroys all resources."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Module version/source changes require `terraform init` to install the new version before planning; Terraform will not silently fetch it during plan.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/init","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform init"},{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/modules/syntax","label":"Terraform Docs — Module Registry"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$What happens if you change a registry module's pinned `version` and run plan without re-initializing?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Terraform Modules$tv2$, 3, $tv2$TRUE_FALSE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$True or False: A child module cannot directly read the root module's variables; values must be passed in explicitly as module arguments.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"True"},{"id":"b","text":"False"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$True. Modules are encapsulated — a child only receives values its caller explicitly passes as input arguments; it cannot reach into the root's variables.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/modules","label":"Terraform Docs — Modules"},{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/values/variables","label":"Terraform Docs — Input Variables"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$True or False: A child module cannot directly read the root module's variables; values must be passed in explicitly as module arguments.$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Terraform Modules$tv2$, 2, $tv2$MULTI$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Select ALL valid `module` block arguments/meta-arguments.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"source"},{"id":"b","text":"version"},{"id":"c","text":"for_each"},{"id":"d","text":"backend"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a","b","c"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`source`, `version`, and meta-arguments like `for_each`/`count`/`depends_on`/`providers` are valid on module blocks. `backend` is configured in the `terraform` block, not on a module.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/modules","label":"Terraform Docs — Modules"},{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/meta-arguments/for_each","label":"Terraform Docs — for_each"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Select ALL valid `module` block arguments/meta-arguments.$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Use Terraform Outside the Core Workflow$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which command associates an EXISTING manually-created S3 bucket with `aws_s3_bucket.logs` in state?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"terraform import aws_s3_bucket.logs my-bucket-name"},{"id":"b","text":"terraform apply -import"},{"id":"c","text":"terraform state add aws_s3_bucket.logs"},{"id":"d","text":"terraform refresh aws_s3_bucket.logs"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`terraform import <address> <id>` binds an existing object to a resource address in state. There is no `state add` subcommand, and refresh/apply do not import.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/import","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform import"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which command associates an EXISTING manually-created S3 bucket with `aws_s3_bucket.logs` in state?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Use Terraform Outside the Core Workflow$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$You want to evaluate `cidrsubnet("10.0.0.0/16", 8, 2)` quickly without applying anything. Best tool?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"terraform console"},{"id":"b","text":"terraform apply"},{"id":"c","text":"terraform import"},{"id":"d","text":"terraform fmt"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`terraform console` is an interactive REPL perfect for testing function expressions like `cidrsubnet(...)` without changing infrastructure.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/console","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform console"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$You want to evaluate `cidrsubnet("10.0.0.0/16", 8, 2)` quickly without applying anything. Best tool?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Use Terraform Outside the Core Workflow$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which command synchronizes state with real resources without proposing or making infrastructure changes (modern form)?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"terraform apply -refresh-only"},{"id":"b","text":"terraform validate"},{"id":"c","text":"terraform fmt"},{"id":"d","text":"terraform import"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`terraform apply -refresh-only` updates state to match real resources without altering infrastructure (the modern replacement for standalone `terraform refresh`).$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/state","label":"Terraform Docs — State"},{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/plan","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform plan"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which command synchronizes state with real resources without proposing or making infrastructure changes (modern form)?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Use Terraform Outside the Core Workflow$tv2$, 3, $tv2$TRUE_FALSE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$True or False: `terraform_remote_state` only exposes the OTHER configuration's declared outputs, not its full resource attributes.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"True"},{"id":"b","text":"False"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$True. The `terraform_remote_state` data source surfaces only the root outputs the other configuration explicitly exports, not arbitrary internal resource attributes.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/state/remote-state-data","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform_remote_state"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$True or False: `terraform_remote_state` only exposes the OTHER configuration's declared outputs, not its full resource attributes.$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Implement and Maintain State$tv2$, 1, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$What does Terraform state primarily track?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"The mapping between configuration resources and real infrastructure objects, plus metadata."},{"id":"b","text":"The Terraform CLI download history."},{"id":"c","text":"The user's shell command history."},{"id":"d","text":"Provider plugin source code."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$State maps declared resources to real-world objects and stores metadata Terraform needs for planning. It is not a command history or plugin source store.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/state","label":"Terraform Docs — State"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$What does Terraform state primarily track?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Implement and Maintain State$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which command deletes the workspace named "temp" (must not be the current/only one)?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"terraform workspace delete temp"},{"id":"b","text":"terraform workspace rm temp"},{"id":"c","text":"terraform delete workspace temp"},{"id":"d","text":"terraform workspace drop temp"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`terraform workspace delete <name>` removes a workspace (you cannot delete the currently selected or default workspace). The other forms are invalid.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/state/workspaces","label":"Terraform Docs — Workspaces"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which command deletes the workspace named "temp" (must not be the current/only one)?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Implement and Maintain State$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$A resource block was renamed from `aws_instance.app` to `aws_instance.web`. Without intervention, what does plan show?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"A no-op."},{"id":"b","text":"Destroy of `aws_instance.app` and create of `aws_instance.web` (unless you `state mv` or use a `moved` block)."},{"id":"c","text":"Only an in-place update."},{"id":"d","text":"An import prompt."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["b"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Renaming an address makes Terraform see the old one as removed and the new one as added (destroy+create). `terraform state mv` or a `moved` block preserves the object.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/state","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform state"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$A resource block was renamed from `aws_instance.app` to `aws_instance.web`. Without intervention, what does plan show?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Implement and Maintain State$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which is a valid reason to use a remote backend instead of local state for a team?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Shared, centralized state with locking to prevent conflicting writes."},{"id":"b","text":"It removes the need to write configuration."},{"id":"c","text":"It makes provider plugins unnecessary."},{"id":"d","text":"It disables the plan step."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Remote backends provide shared state plus locking so teams do not corrupt state with concurrent applies. They do not remove config, providers, or planning.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/backend","label":"Terraform Docs — Backends"},{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/state/locking","label":"Terraform Docs — State Locking"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which is a valid reason to use a remote backend instead of local state for a team?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Implement and Maintain State$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$You want Terraform to stop managing a resource but keep the real object alive. Which command?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"terraform state rm aws_instance.legacy"},{"id":"b","text":"terraform destroy -target=aws_instance.legacy"},{"id":"c","text":"terraform apply -replace=aws_instance.legacy"},{"id":"d","text":"terraform taint aws_instance.legacy"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`terraform state rm` removes the resource from state so Terraform no longer manages it while leaving the real object intact. destroy deletes it; replace/taint recreate it.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/state","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform state"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$You want Terraform to stop managing a resource but keep the real object alive. Which command?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Implement and Maintain State$tv2$, 2, $tv2$TRUE_FALSE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$True or False: Hand-editing the raw state JSON is discouraged; the supported approach is the `terraform state` subcommands.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"True"},{"id":"b","text":"False"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$True. Manual edits risk corrupting state; HashiCorp recommends the `terraform state` family (mv/rm/show/list) for safe modifications.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/state","label":"Terraform Docs — terraform state"},{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/state","label":"Terraform Docs — State"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$True or False: Hand-editing the raw state JSON is discouraged; the supported approach is the `terraform state` subcommands.$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Implement and Maintain State$tv2$, 3, $tv2$MULTI$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Select ALL true statements about remote backends and locking.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"Some backends support automatic state locking during writes."},{"id":"b","text":"Locking helps prevent state corruption from concurrent operations."},{"id":"c","text":"Not all backends support locking."},{"id":"d","text":"Locking eliminates the need for state entirely."}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a","b","c"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$Many backends lock state during writes to prevent concurrent corruption, but not all backends support locking. Locking does not eliminate the need for state.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/state/locking","label":"Terraform Docs — State Locking"},{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/backend","label":"Terraform Docs — Backends"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Select ALL true statements about remote backends and locking.$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Read, Generate, and Modify Configuration$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which meta-argument creates resource instances keyed by each element of a set or map?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"for_each"},{"id":"b","text":"count"},{"id":"c","text":"lifecycle"},{"id":"d","text":"provider"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`for_each` instantiates one resource per element of a map/set, keyed by the element key (stable across changes). `count` uses numeric indexes; lifecycle/provider serve other roles.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/meta-arguments/for_each","label":"Terraform Docs — for_each"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which meta-argument creates resource instances keyed by each element of a set or map?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Read, Generate, and Modify Configuration$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$You want Terraform to create a new replacement resource BEFORE destroying the old one to avoid downtime. Which lifecycle setting?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"create_before_destroy = true"},{"id":"b","text":"prevent_destroy = true"},{"id":"c","text":"ignore_changes = all"},{"id":"d","text":"replace_triggered_by = []"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`lifecycle { create_before_destroy = true }` provisions the replacement before destroying the original, minimizing downtime. The other settings address deletion protection, drift ignoring, and forced replacement triggers.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/meta-arguments/lifecycle","label":"Terraform Docs — lifecycle"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$You want Terraform to create a new replacement resource BEFORE destroying the old one to avoid downtime. Which lifecycle setting?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Read, Generate, and Modify Configuration$tv2$, 2, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which lifecycle setting tells Terraform to ignore external changes to specified attributes during plan?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"ignore_changes"},{"id":"b","text":"prevent_destroy"},{"id":"c","text":"create_before_destroy"},{"id":"d","text":"depends_on"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$`lifecycle { ignore_changes = [..] }` makes Terraform disregard drift on listed attributes so it does not try to revert them. The others control destruction order/protection or dependencies.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/meta-arguments/lifecycle","label":"Terraform Docs — lifecycle"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which lifecycle setting tells Terraform to ignore external changes to specified attributes during plan?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Read, Generate, and Modify Configuration$tv2$, 3, $tv2$SINGLE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$Which function reads and returns the contents of a file at plan/apply time?$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"file(\"script.sh\")"},{"id":"b","text":"read(\"script.sh\")"},{"id":"c","text":"load(\"script.sh\")"},{"id":"d","text":"open(\"script.sh\")"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$The built-in `file(path)` function returns the file's contents as a string. `read`/`load`/`open` are not Terraform functions.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/functions","label":"Terraform Docs — Built-in Functions"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$Which function reads and returns the contents of a file at plan/apply time?$tv2$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $tv2$Read, Generate, and Modify Configuration$tv2$, 2, $tv2$TRUE_FALSE$tv2$::"QType", $tv2$True or False: `depends_on` should be used for explicit ordering only when Terraform cannot infer a dependency automatically from references.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"id":"a","text":"True"},{"id":"b","text":"False"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$["a"]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$True. Terraform infers most dependencies from expression references; `depends_on` is for the rare cases where an implicit dependency cannot be detected.$tv2$, $tv2$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/meta-arguments/depends_on","label":"Terraform Docs — Meta-Arguments"},{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/resources/behavior","label":"Terraform Docs — Resource Dependencies"}]$tv2$::jsonb, $tv2$PUBLISHED$tv2$::"QStatus", $tv2$manual:terraform-seed$tv2$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.slug = $tv2$hashicorp-terraform-associate-p3$tv2$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $tv2$True or False: `depends_on` should be used for explicit ordering only when Terraform cannot infer a dependency automatically from references.$tv2$);
